<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-028-448  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 028 448.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Jan 8 1990 v6 n1 p37(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IXI's X.desktop interface makes inroads with Unix developers.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Smith, Gina.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Cambridge, England-based IXI Ltd debuts X.desktop 2.0, a graphicaluser interface aimed at easing management and use of Unixcomputers running the X Windows standard.andP;  X.desktop 2.0 willsupport Motif, the Open Software Foundation's graphical-designtoolset.andP;  With X.desktop 2.0, users can start programs, delete,copy and create directories and files via on-screen icons.andO;Versions of X.desktop 2.0 cost about $495 per user.andP;  Severalhardware and software vendors are selling or bundling X.desktopwith their Unix products and IBM is considering adopting X.desktopfor its AIX operating system.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   IXI Ltd. (product introduction).andO;Product:   X.desktop 2.0 (Graphical user interface) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     UNIXGraphical User InterfaceProduct IntroductionX Windows (Standard).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Gina SmithandM;As IBM continues to examine the X.desktop user interface for possibleincorporation into its Unix offerings, users of the graphical interface arefinding that the once-obscure tool is heading toward the mainstream.andM;More than a year after England's IXI Ltd. released the Unix interface into afragmented marketplace, several software and hardware vendors are now sellingor bundling X.desktop for use with their Unix offerings.andM;In addition to serving as the interface portion of The Santa Cruz OperationInc.'s Open Desktop Unix offering, X.desktop has been adopted by Sony Corp.andO;for use in its NEWS workstations and by NCR Corp. in its multiuser Towerviewsystems.andM;Furthermore, at Comdex/Fall last November IBM announced it is investigatingX.desktop as the graphical user interface for future AIX system software.andM;X.desktop 2.0's graphical desktop paradigm shields users from the crypticUnix command prompt, said Ray Anderson, president of the Cambridge, England,firm.andP;  With X.desktop 2.0, users can start programs, copy, delete and createfiles and directories by manipulating on-screen icons.andP;  The software alsoincludes menu-configuration features that allow managers to customize theinterface for specific users or work groups, he said.andM;The graphical user interface is designed to make Unix machines running XWindows easier to manage and use.andP;  The newest version of the interface,X.desktop 2.0, can also be run on top of Motif, the Open SoftwareFoundation's set of graphical design tools, Anderson said.andM;&quot;Until recently, you'd be hard-pressed to sit in front of a Unix machine fora half hour and even begin to use it,&quot; he said, explaining that IXI addedMotif compatibility to X.desktop 2.0 in an effort to become part of the Unixstandardization trend.andM;X.desktop's ease of use may make it more attractive to firms moving to Unix,said Jerry McEachern, operations manager at the Houston Chronicle newspaper.andO;The Chronicle is in the process of moving from a DOS-based PC XTs toUnix-based Sun workstations and X Window terminals, he said.andM;&quot;A couple of years ago, we would have never considered moving from DOS toUnix,&quot; he said, explaining that X.desktop makes migrating to Unix easier.andM;Retail versions of X.desktop 2.0, priced at approximately $495 per user, arenow available for the Sun-3, Sun-4, Apollo Domain, Hewlett-Packard Co.andP;  9000,Mac II and 386-based PCs.andM;IXI's U.S.andP;  distributor, Unipress Software Inc., can be reached in Edison,N.J.andP;  at (201) 985-8000.andO;</TEXT></DOC>